column168: ON OCTOBER 1, 1986 AT APPROXIMENTLY 9:40 AM I, ELLIE LAPIETRA, OPERATION MA NAGER WAS INFORMED OF A CHEMICAL SPILL IN THE TRL.  AT THAT TIME I WENT INT O THE TRL TO INVESTIGATE THE ACCIDENT.  I TOLD THE DRIVER TO PUT THE DRUM O N ITS SIDE WHILE I GO AND LOOK FOR SOMETHING TO PLUG THE PUNCTURED DRUM, HO WEVER SINCE I COULDN'T FIND ANY PUTTY TO PLUG THE DRUM I TRIED TO PLUG IT U P WITH MY GUM. THE PUNCTURE WAS TO SEVERE SO I HAD THE DRIVER MOVE THE TRL IN THE YARD AWAY FROM THE DOCK.  I THEN REPORTED THE ACCIDENT TO SAM BERMAN , JERRY DERRICK & RICK GROVER.  THE GATES FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE .  THEY WERE HERE WITHIN 15 MINUTES. THE POLICE AND AMBULANCE WERE ALSO ON THE SCENE. WHILE THE FIRE DEPT WERE TAKING ALL THE FACTS THE AMBULANCE ATTE NDENTS WERE MAKING SURE THE EMPLOYEES WERE GIVEN MEDICAL ATTENTION. THE FIR E DEPT PUT THE PUNCTURED DRUM INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS WAS THERN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL THEY USED A FLOOR ABSORBENT. THE CAU SE OF THE ALARM WAS THE FUMES AND BEING FATAL IF INHALED. RECOMMENDATION FO R FURTHER ELIMINATION ARE; PROPER AWARENESS AND HANDLING PROCEDURES ON OUR PART AND ALSO BEING SURE THE DRUM DEVICE HAS A SECURE STOPPER ON IT SO THAT THE FORK LIFT WON'T SLIP OR PUNTURE THE DRUM NEXT TO THE ONE BEING LIFTED.

column168: A) DURING REQUIRED DAILY INSPECTIONS TWO DRUMS WERE NOTICED LEAKING. THE TWO GALLONS TOTAL LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM SEAMS OF BOTH DRUMS. THE DRUMS MAY HAVE WEAKENED DURING THE PHYSICAL MOVEMENT OF THE DRUMS OR WERE JUST STRUC- TURAL DEFECTIVE. BOTH DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL CLEANED UP WITH CLAY FOR DISPOSAL. B) DURING THE REQUIRED DAILY INSPECTION A DRUM WAS NOTICED LEAKING. APPROX- IMATELY 1 GALLON OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM A POORLY SECURED AND POORLY MADE SIDE BUNG OPENING. THE BUNG WAS SLIGHTLY STRIPPED ALLOWING THE SOLVENT TO SLOWLY LEAK OUT. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL ABSORBED AND DRUMMED. THE ORIGINAL DRUM AND SPILL RESIDUE WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN AN EPA APPROVED METHOD. C) DURING THE DAILY FACILITY INSPECTION A DRUM OF PCB FLOURESCENT LIGHT BALLASTS (NOT TSCA REGULATED) WAS NOTICED LEAKING. APPROXIMATELY 2 QUARTS OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM. THE AMOUNT OF MAT- ERIAL INVOLVED WAS LESS THE RQ VALUE AND THEREFORE WAS NOT REQUIRED TO BE FORMALLY REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. THIS WAS CONFIRMED BY LT J.G. MIDDLEBROOKS OF THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WHICH WAS CALLED AS A PRE CAUTIONARY MEASURE. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL CLEAN ED UP WITH KEROSENE. THE DRUM WAS LOCATED IN WAREHOUSE BIN NUMBER TWO WHICH WAS CONSTRUCTED TO CONFORM WITH CFT 40 PART 761.65(B).

DOCKMAN ROBERT ELLIOTT OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND THE CARTON FELL OUT FROM THE TOP OF THE FREIGHT SMASHING 1 BOTTLE.  IT SPLASHED AN HIS SHOES AND ON TO THE APRAN OF THE DOCK.  WE CLEANED UP WITH SPEDDY-DRY AND PUT REMAINING BOTTLES AND THE RESIDUE IN AN O/S TRAILER IN THE YARD.  ELLIOT WENT TO THE HOSPITAL AND WAS CHECKED OUT.  HE WAS TOLD TO TRASH ALL OF HIS CLOTHES AND WORK BOOTS.  HE FELT SICKM TO HIS STOMACH FROM INHALING THE FUMES.  HE WAS AT WORK AT HIS NEXT REQUIRED SHIFT.

ON MONDAY, OCT 27, 1986, AT APPROX. 9:00 PM, THE C-3 YARD ASSIGNMENT DETECT ED AND REPORTED A HEAVY SMELL OF CHLORINE WHILE COUPLING TANK CAR PROX28005 WHICH CONTAINED CHLORINE. AT THE TIME THE ODOR WAS DETECTED, CAR PROX28005 WAS SITTING ON B TRACK, 31 CAR LENGTHS FROM THE SOUTH END. TANK CAR PROX28 005 WAS MOVED FROM B TRACK TO #20 TRACK IN THE NORTH YARD TO ISOLATE THE CA R AND TO PUT THE CAR IN A BETTER POSITIN TO BE OBSERVED AND REPAIRED.  THE CONDUCTER AND THE BRAKEMAN CLAIMED TO HAVE BREATHED SOME OF THE FUMES AND L ATER COMPLAINED OF ILL EFFECTS FROM THE FUMES, BUT DIDNOT WANT MEDICAL ATTE NTION.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 9:00 PM BY THE ASSISTANT TRAIN MASTER AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, CIL INC OF MONTREAL, PROVIDENCE OF QUE BEC, CANADA. THE SHIPPER ACTIVATED THE CHEMICAL MANUFACTURER' ASSC. OF CHLO RINE RESPONSE TEAM AND MR. CHARLES G MCCUEN OF OCCIDENTAL PETROLEUM CO., IN C. OF DELAWARE CITY, DELAWARE CALLED AT 9:25 PM AND, AFTER BEING ADVISED OF THE SITUATION, ADVISED HE AND ANOTHER TEAM WOULD BE RESPONDING. MR. MCCUEN CALLED BACK AT 10:50 PM AND ADVISED THE TEAM WAS LEAVING DELAWARE CITY AND WOULD BE IN RICHMOND IN ABOUT 5 HOURS.  MR. JAMES H. RADER, THE DISTRICT I NSPECTOR FOR THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, WAS NOTIFIED AT 9:25 PM AND HE ADVIS ED US HE WOULD BE RESPONDING FROM NORTHERN VIRGINIA .....CONTINUED ON ATTAC HED SHEET.  REMARKS - CONTINUED.  ALL APPROPRIATE RF&P PERSONNEL WERE NOTIF IED. A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR WAS MADE AND A SLIGHT ODOR OF CHLORINE WAS DETECTED, ALONG WITH THE SOUND OF PRESSURE RELEASING FROM THE DOME AREA OF THE CAR. AT 11:30 P.M. MR. RADER ARRIVED AND MADE A CLOSE IN- SPECTION OF THE DOME AREA OF THE CAR. MR. RADER FOUND THAT THE FOUR NUTS THAT HOLD THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WERE NOT SECURELY TIGHTENED, THUS ALLOW ING THE CHLORINE VAPOR TO SEEP OUT AROUND THE GASKET. MR. RADER TIGHTENED THE NUTS AND DECREASED THE LEAKAGE, BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK TOTALY. AT 3:30 A.M. ON TUESDAY, OCTOBER 28, 1986, MR. MCCUEN AND MR. NEIL, THE MEMBERS OF THE CHLORINE RESPONSE TEAM, ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD. AFTER EVALUAT- ING THE SITUATION, WITH THE AID OF MR. RADER, THE RESPONSE TEAM, USING A LARGE TEE BAR WRENCH, TIGHTENED THE NUTS SUFFICIENTLY TO STOP THE LEAK. THE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AND THE DOME SECURED AND SEALED AT 5:35 A.M. TANK CAR PROX 28005 WAS RELEASED FOR SERVICE AT 5:45 A.M. TO BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE, CIL CORPORATION OF AMERICA, C/O SUFFOLK CHEMICAL COMPANY, SUBURBAN DRIVE, SUFFOLK, VIRGINIA.
